'''''Juma and the Magic Jinn''''' is a children's [[picture book]] written by Joy Anderson and illustrated by [[Charles Mikolaycak]]. First published in [[1986 in literature|1986]], this folktale with an African setting tells the story of a fictional, [[daydreaming]] boy named Juma who is living on the real [[Lamu Island]] just off the East coast of [[Kenya]]. Desiring to be some place where he won't have to study or behave, Juma seeks the help of a magical [[Genie|jinn]] (in English, a genie), a decision which leads Juma on misadventures. In the same year the book was published, ''Juma and the Magic Jinn'' won a [[Golden Kite Award#1986|1986 Golden Kite Award]] for Mikolaycak's illustrations. These illustrations additionally played a role in Mikolaycak receiving the 1987 Kerland Award "in recognition of singular attainments in the creation of children's literature."

==Background==
''Juma and the Magic Jinn'' is an [[Folklore|African folklore]] inspired children's book written Joy Anderson and illustrated by [[Charles Mikolaycak]] (26 January 1937- 23 June 1993).<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=March 8, 1987|edition=Sunday|journal=[[The New York Times Book Review]]|title=Juma and the magic jinn|volume=92|pages=31|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Peterman|first=Peggy|date=November 20, 1990|work=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|title=Give a Gift of Heritage|section=Floridian|pages=1D|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FLgMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VV8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6970,5817514&dq=magic-jinn}}</ref><ref name="Continuum">{{cite book|last=Cullinan|first=Bernice E.|date=2005|title=The Continuum Encyclopedia of Children's Literature|pages=547|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group]]|isbn=0826417787|quote=|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0LyutQg6mroC&pg=PA547&dq=%22Magic+jinn%22&as_brr=3}}</ref> The book illustrations use double-page spreads to capture a sequential picture style containing an attention to details, colors, and African setting patterns.<ref name="Continuum"/> Targeted for children ages 6-9, the [[folktale]] takes place on [[Lamu Island|Lamu]],<ref name="Favorite">{{cite book|last=Raines|first=Shirley C.|date=1994|title=450 More Story Stretchers for the Primary Grades: Activities to Expand Children's Favorite Books|pages=180|publisher=Gryphon House, Inc.|isbn=0876591675|quote=|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Ghy2YOamgZwC&pg=PA180&dq=%22Magic+jinn%22&as_brr=3}}</ref> a real island just off the East coast of [[Kenya]] that was established as early as the fourteenth century by [[Arab]] traders and is populated with [[Moslems]].<ref name="choices">{{cite news|last=Loer|first=Stephanie|date=February 15, 1987|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|title=Picture book choices|section=Books|pages=B24|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?direct-0=0EADEDD8483F2FA7}}</ref> It was Anderson's visit to the island that inspired the [[University of Central Florida]] adjunct professor to write about a present-day boy who had a fairy-tale adventure.<ref name="Juma">{{cite book|last=Anderson|first=Joy|date=1986|title=Juma and the Magic Jinn|pages=|publisher=Lothrop, Lee & Shepard Books|isbn=0688054439|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=y4aZGQAACAAJ&dq=juma+and+the+magic+jinn}}</ref>

==Plot==
[[Image:Lamu coast.jpg|thumb|left|180px|View of the seaside on [[Lamu Island]]]]
On the [[seafaring]] Lamu Island, families traditionally keep a jinn jar at home.<ref name="choices"/> The jinn jar is a container that hold a supernatural being in [[Islam]] and [[Arabian mythology]] called a [[Genie|jinn]] (in English, a genie).<ref name="choices"/> The jinn jar is kept sealed because the owners do not know if their magic jinn is good or evil, which makes people of Lamu Island generally afraid of the jinns.<ref name="choices"/>

The story opens with a young student named Juma [[daydreaming]] in a school instead of doing his mathematics.<ref name="choices"/><ref name="Connecting">{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Rebecca L.|date=1996|title=Connecting Cultures: A Guide to Multicultural Literature for Children|pages=12|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|isbn=0835237605|quote=|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=a9RySF9cawUC&pg=PA12&dq=%22Magic+jinn%22&as_brr=3}}</ref> Since the young Juma concentrates more on his own directions of thought rather than the lessons being taught, the teacher sends Juma home.<ref name="choices"/> On the way home, he comes across his mother buying fish at the shore.<ref name="Juma"/> His mother admonishes his daydreaming in school and suggests that Juma may be better off working with his father to cut [[Mangrove|mangrove poles]].<ref name="Juma"/> She instruction Juma to go home, but instructs Juma to not touch the jinn jar.<ref name="Juma"/>

At home, Juma disobeys his mother's prior instructions and removes the cork sealing the jinn jar and calls the jinn.<ref name="choices"/><ref name="Connecting"/><ref name="bookshelf">{{cite news|last=|first=|date=March 8, 1987|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Children's Books: Bookshelf|section=7|pages=731|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE4DB163CF93BA35750C0A961948260}}</ref> Juma is skeptical about his efforts and does not believe in magic.<ref name="Favorite"/> However, the magic jinn appears, in this instance as a "young woman with black and smiling catlike eyes," whose dark hair is tied with amber beads.<ref name="Juma"/> The jinn offers to grant Juma wishes.<ref name="Favorite"/> Desiring to be some place where he won't have to study or behave,<ref name="Favorite"/> Juma formulates his wishes to overcome his need for schooling, particularly math and writing ("sums and script").<ref name="Reading">{{cite news|last=Aborn|first=Carlene M.|date=February 1, 1991|work=[[St Petersburg Times]]|title=Reading list|section=Floridian|pages=15X|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=}}</ref> The magic jinn grants some of Juma's wishes and is sent away from his home on what turns out to be misadventures.<ref name="choices"/><ref name="bookshelf"/> Eventually, Juma is able to get home again but arrives with new appreciation of his home and family and realization that learning can be exciting and fun.<ref name="choices"/><ref name="bookshelf"/><ref name="Reading"/>

==Reaction==
''Juma and the Magic Jinn'' was published in 1986.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zeiger|first=Hanna B.|date=November 1986|work=[[Horn Book Magazine]]|title=Juma and the magic jinn|volume=62|pages=729|publisher=[[The Gale Group]]|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://www.hbook.com/magazine/}}</ref> In that same year, ''Juma and the Magic Jinn'' was awarded Honor Book in the picture book illustration category of [[Golden Kite Award]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Marks|first=Diana F.|date=2006|title=Children's Book Award Handbook|pages=349|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|isbn=1591583047|quote=|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=yNxFOzOpZMIC&pg=PA349&dq=%22Magic+jinn%22&as_brr=3}}</ref> In February 1987, the dark, rich color illustrations in the African folklore book were singled out as strong and handsome elements that emphasize the mystery of the tale.<ref name="choices"/> These and other illustrations lead to Mikolaycak receiving the 1987 Kerland Award "in recognition of singular attainments in the creation of children's literature."<ref name="Continuum"/> From September 12, 1993 to May 1, 1994, the McKissick Museum at the [[University of South Carolina]] exhibited ''Juma and the Magic Jinn''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wiggins|first=William H.|date=1994|title=Jubilation!: African American Celebrations in the Southeast|pages=51|publisher=[[University of South Carolina Press]]|isbn=157003009X|quote=|accessdate=7 December 2008|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ecq9Jd_ztoMC&pg=PA51&dq=%22Magic+jinn%22&as_brr=3}}</ref>

